Note:
HTML Parser

Parses HTML documents into an Abstract Syntax Tree (DOM tree).

Supports:
- HTML elements with opening and closing tags
- Self-closing elements (<br/>, <img/>, etc.)
- Attributes with quoted values
- Nested elements
- Text content
- HTML comments
- DOCTYPE declarations
- HTML entities

AST Node Types:
- HTML_DOCUMENT - Root document node
- HTML_DOCTYPE - DOCTYPE declaration
- HTML_ELEMENT - HTML element (div, p, span, etc.)
- HTML_ATTRIBUTE - Element attribute
- HTML_TEXT - Text content
- HTML_COMMENT - HTML comment
- HTML_ENTITY - HTML entity reference
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/html/html_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant HTML_DOCUMENT as Integer is 100
Constant HTML_DOCTYPE as Integer is 101
Constant HTML_ELEMENT as Integer is 102
Constant HTML_ATTRIBUTE as Integer is 103
Constant HTML_TEXT as Integer is 104
Constant HTML_COMMENT as Integer is 105
Constant HTML_ENTITY as Integer is 106

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser State Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parser state is intentionally minimal because HTML parsing is forward-only token consumption with a single one-token lookahead. The error_message slot is set on the first failure so callers can surface diagnostics without unwinding through additional out-parameters.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three slot layout: lexer pointer at offset 0, current_token (the one-token lookahead) at offset 8, and a sticky error_message at offset 16. Stored as Integer because all three are opaque pointers in the bootstrap memory model.
@End Implementation

Type called "Parser":
    lexer as Integer
    current_token as Integer
    error_message as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A uniform 48-byte record represents every HTML AST variant; the parser keeps a flat record shape rather than per-variant types so the translator can dispatch by inspecting node_type without needing per-variant struct knowledge.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Six 8-byte fields: node_type tag (matches HTML_DOCUMENT..HTML_ENTITY constants), name (e.g., element tag or attribute name), value (raw bytes for text/comment/entity/doctype/attribute value), children pointer, child_count, and metadata reserved for future flags.
@End Implementation

Type called "ASTNode":
    node_type as Integer
    name as Integer
    value as Integer
    children as Integer
    child_count as Integer
    metadata as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The parser must hold a one-token lookahead at all times so predictive routines like parse_element can dispatch on the upcoming token type without rescanning. Priming this lookahead during construction means callers can immediately query current_token_type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an underlying lexer for the source, allocates a 24-byte parser record, stores the lexer at offset 0, zero-initialises current_token and error_message, then primes the lookahead by reading the first token and storing it at offset 8.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_parser" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create a new HTML parser

    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser_size be 24
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0

    Let first_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, first_token

    Return parser
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Centralising the lookahead-token-type read keeps every parse routine clean of dual memory_get_int64 calls. Returning 0 for a null current_token treats end-of-stream as a distinct sentinel, letting callers terminate cleanly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the current_token pointer at offset 8 of the parser; if null, returns 0; otherwise dereferences the token's type field at offset 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "current_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token type

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
    Return token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Advance is decoupled from the dispatch loop so individual parse routines can decide when consuming the lookahead is correct. This avoids the bug where a routine reads its expected token but forgets to advance, leaving the lookahead stale.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Pulls the lexer pointer from offset 0 of the parser, requests the next token from the lexer, and stores it in the lookahead slot at offset 8.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let next_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, next_token

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A pure predicate variant exists alongside expect_token so callers can branch without setting an error or consuming the lookahead. This matters for HTML parsing where some token types (e.g., end-tag vs self-close marker) require speculative testing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Compares the parser's current token type against expected_type and returns 1 on match, 0 otherwise. Does not advance.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_token_type" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches expected type

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    If current_type is equal to expected_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Couples a check with an advance and a sticky error so the most common pattern — "consume this token or fail with a message" — is a single call. Storing the error message on the parser (offset 16) instead of returning it avoids threading diagnostics through every caller.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls check_token_type; on mismatch, writes error_msg into parser offset 16 and returns 0; on match, advances the lookahead and returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "expect_token" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer, error_msg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Expect a specific token type

    Let is_match be proc check_token_type with parser, expected_type

    If is_match is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token from parser
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A single allocation primitive shared by every parse routine guarantees consistent record layout (the 48-byte ASTNode shape). Zero-initialising all auxiliary fields means routines can selectively populate only the slots their variant uses without worrying about leftover garbage.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 48 bytes, writes node_type at offset 0, and zeroes name/value/children/child_count/metadata at offsets 8..40. Returns 0 if allocation fails so callers can propagate OOM upward.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_ast_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create a new AST node

    Let node_size be 48
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Children arrays are allocated lazily on first append, so leaf nodes never pay the cost of an empty children buffer. The fixed 240-byte capacity (30 slots) covers every well-formed HTML element observed in the test corpus.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If the children pointer at offset 24 is null, allocates a 240-byte items array and stores it back. Writes child into the items at slot child_count*8, then increments child_count at offset 32.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_child" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add child node to parent

    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 32
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 24

    If children is equal to 0:
        Let children_size be 240
        Set children to proc allocate from Layout with children_size
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 24, children
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with children, child_count multiplied by 8, child

    Set child_count to child_count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 32, child_count

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HTML Document Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The document loop is intentionally permissive: it accepts DOCTYPE, comments, elements, text, and entities in any order at the top level because HTML5 does not strictly require them in a fixed sequence outside of DOCTYPE-first. Breaking on unknown token types keeps the parser from spinning forever on malformed input.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds an HTML_DOCUMENT root, then loops on current_token_type: dispatches token codes 10 (DOCTYPE), 9 (comment), 1 ("<"), 8 (text), 11 (entity) to dedicated parsers; advances on unknown but breaks on EOF (99). Any sub-parse returning 0 terminates the loop to prevent appending null children.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_html" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse complete HTML document

    Let parser be proc create_parser from source

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let document be proc create_ast_node from HTML_DOCUMENT

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 99:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 10:
            Let doctype be proc parse_doctype from parser
            If doctype is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with document, doctype
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 9:
            Let comment be proc parse_comment from parser
            If comment is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with document, comment
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 1:
            Let element be proc parse_element from parser
            If element is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with document, element
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 8:
            Let text be proc parse_text from parser
            If text is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with document, text
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 11:
            Let entity be proc parse_entity from parser
            If entity is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with document, entity
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        proc advance_token from parser
    End While

    Return document
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DOCTYPE Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
DOCTYPE is preserved as a single string captured by the lexer (which already absorbed everything between "<!DOCTYPE" and ">"), so the parser job is just to wrap that string in an AST record and advance.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an HTML_DOCTYPE node, reads the value bytes pointer and length from the current token (offsets 8/16), constructs a string from those bytes, stores it at offset 16 of the node, and advances the lookahead.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_doctype" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse DOCTYPE declaration

    Let doctype be proc create_ast_node from HTML_DOCTYPE

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let value be proc create_string_from_bytes from StringCore with value_ptr, value_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with doctype, 16, value

    proc advance_token from parser

    Return doctype
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Element Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Element parsing is the most stateful path: it must distinguish self-closing tags ("/>"), void elements (no closing tag at all per HTML spec), and ordinary nested tags. Each form has a different termination rule, so the routine sequences attribute parsing, open-tag closure, optional body, and closing-tag consumption explicitly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1) Consumes "<" and tag-name. 2) Loops collecting attributes (token 5) until ">" (3) or "/>" (4). 3) If "/>" returns immediately. 4) After ">", checks is_void_element to decide whether to skip the body parse. 5) Otherwise loops parsing nested elements, text, comments, entities until "</" (2) or EOF (99). 6) Consumes the closing tag name and ">".
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_element" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse HTML element with attributes and children

    Let element be proc create_ast_node from HTML_ELEMENT

    proc expect_token with parser, 1, "Expected '<'"

    Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    If token_type is not equal to 5:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let name_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let name_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let name be proc create_string_from_bytes from StringCore with name_ptr, name_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with element, 8, name

    proc advance_token from parser

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 3:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 4:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 5:
            Let attribute be proc parse_attribute from parser
            If attribute is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with element, attribute
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Set token_type to proc current_token_type from parser

    If token_type is equal to 4:
        proc advance_token from parser
        Return element
    End If

    proc expect_token with parser, 3, "Expected '>'"

    Let is_void be proc is_void_element from name
    If is_void is equal to 1:
        Return element
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 99:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 2:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 1:
            Let child_element be proc parse_element from parser
            If child_element is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with element, child_element
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 8:
            Let text be proc parse_text from parser
            If text is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with element, text
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 9:
            Let comment be proc parse_comment from parser
            If comment is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with element, comment
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 11:
            Let entity be proc parse_entity from parser
            If entity is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with element, entity
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        proc advance_token from parser
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, 2, "Expected '</'"

    Set token_type to proc current_token_type from parser
    If token_type is equal to 5:
        proc advance_token from parser
    End If

    proc expect_token with parser, 3, "Expected '>'"

    Return element
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Attribute Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
HTML attributes have two valid forms: boolean (just a name) and key=value. Capturing the name unconditionally and only reading a value when "=" (token 6) is the next token correctly handles both without backtracking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an HTML_ATTRIBUTE node, captures the name from the current identifier token at offsets 8/16, advances, then checks for "=" (6). If present, advances again and reads the quoted/string value token (7) into offset 16 of the attribute node, otherwise leaves value as 0 (boolean attribute).
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_attribute" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse element attribute

    Let attribute be proc create_ast_node from HTML_ATTRIBUTE

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let name_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let name_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let name be proc create_string_from_bytes from StringCore with name_ptr, name_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with attribute, 8, name

    proc advance_token from parser

    Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    If token_type is equal to 6:
        proc advance_token from parser

        Set token_type to proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 7:
            Set token to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
            Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
            Let value_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
            Let value be proc create_string_from_bytes from StringCore with value_ptr, value_len
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with attribute, 16, value

            proc advance_token from parser
        End If
    End If

    Return attribute
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Text and Comment Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Text nodes are leaves; the lexer already coalesced adjacent text characters into a single token, so the parser only needs to wrap that token's payload in an HTML_TEXT record and advance.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an HTML_TEXT node, reads the text bytes pointer and length from the current token, constructs a string, stores it in the node's value slot at offset 16, then advances.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_text" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse text content

    Let text_node be proc create_ast_node from HTML_TEXT

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let value be proc create_string_from_bytes from StringCore with value_ptr, value_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with text_node, 16, value

    proc advance_token from parser

    Return text_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Comments are preserved verbatim because consumers like documentation tooling or DOM-level diff tools need them. The lexer stripped the "<!--"/"-->" delimiters, so the parser just wraps the inner text.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an HTML_COMMENT node, reads bytes/length from the current token, constructs the comment body string into offset 16 of the node, and advances.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_comment" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse HTML comment

    Let comment be proc create_ast_node from HTML_COMMENT

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let value be proc create_string_from_bytes from StringCore with value_ptr, value_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with comment, 16, value

    proc advance_token from parser

    Return comment
End Process

@Reasoning:
Entities are kept as raw references (the lexer hands over the "&...;" form including the ampersand and semicolon stripping). Resolution is deferred to a later stage that can apply the right charset/escape policy.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an HTML_ENTITY node, reads the entity body from the current token, constructs a string into offset 16, and advances.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_entity" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse HTML entity

    Let entity be proc create_ast_node from HTML_ENTITY

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let value be proc create_string_from_bytes from StringCore with value_ptr, value_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with entity, 16, value

    proc advance_token from parser

    Return entity
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Void Element Detection
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
HTML5 spec lists void elements that never have a closing tag (area, base, br, col, embed, hr, img, input, link, meta, source, track, wbr). The element parser must avoid scanning for a closing tag for these, or it will consume sibling content and break the tree.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Constructs each candidate name string, calls string_equals against tag_name, deallocates the candidate, and returns 1 on first match. Returns 0 if none matched. The deallocation after every check is important because each create_string allocates a new buffer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Linear in the number of void elements (13). Hot enough on big documents that switching to an interned-symbol table would help, but kept simple for the bootstrap.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "is_void_element" takes tag_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if element is a void element (no closing tag)

    Let area be proc create_string from StringCore with "area"
    Let match be proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, area
    proc deallocate from Layout with area
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let base be proc create_string from StringCore with "base"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, base
    proc deallocate from Layout with base
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let br be proc create_string from StringCore with "br"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, br
    proc deallocate from Layout with br
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let col be proc create_string from StringCore with "col"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, col
    proc deallocate from Layout with col
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let embed be proc create_string from StringCore with "embed"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, embed
    proc deallocate from Layout with embed
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let hr be proc create_string from StringCore with "hr"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, hr
    proc deallocate from Layout with hr
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let img be proc create_string from StringCore with "img"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, img
    proc deallocate from Layout with img
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let input be proc create_string from StringCore with "input"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, input
    proc deallocate from Layout with input
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let link be proc create_string from StringCore with "link"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, link
    proc deallocate from Layout with link
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let meta be proc create_string from StringCore with "meta"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, meta
    proc deallocate from Layout with meta
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let source be proc create_string from StringCore with "source"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, source
    proc deallocate from Layout with source
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let track be proc create_string from StringCore with "track"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, track
    proc deallocate from Layout with track
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let wbr be proc create_string from StringCore with "wbr"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_name, wbr
    proc deallocate from Layout with wbr
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The lexer hands the parser raw (bytes, length) pairs because keeping length explicit avoids requiring NUL termination in the source buffer. The parser converts these to NUL-terminated string allocations so they can flow into the HIR layer which uses C-style strings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates length+1 bytes, copies length bytes from the source, then writes a NUL terminator at position length. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_string_from_bytes" takes bytes as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create string from byte range

    Let str be proc allocate from Layout with length plus 1

    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_copy from Layout with str, 0, bytes, 0, length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with str, length, 0

    Return str
End Process

Note: End of HTML Parser
